# Command ddir

## What does this command do:

Compares two directories recursively, reporting files missing from either side and running side-by-side diffs on files that differ. Hidden files and directories (names starting with `.`) are skipped.

## Installed from

Pre-installed in `~/tools` — clone the tools repo:
```bash
git clone git@github.com:kevinpinscoe/tools.git ~/tools
```

## Command path

For Fedora run: `~/tools/ddir`
For Raspberry Pi run: `~/tools/ddir`
For Mac run: `~/tools/ddir`

## Command documentation

Docs can be found at https://github.com/kevinpinscoe/tools

## Command options

### Usage
    ddir <dir-a> <dir-b>

### Output
    -- Missing <path>          File exists in one directory but not the other
    ** <a> and <b> differ      Side-by-side diff of files with differing content
    Summary statistics printed at the end (file counts, missing, differing)

### Examples
# Compare two directories
ddir ~/Projects/foo ~/backup/foo

# Compare current directory with a backup
ddir . ~/backup/current

### Dependencies

`python3`, `diff`
